<HEADLINE>
<P>
'MEAGER VALUE,' INDEED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I am writing in regard to the article by Mike Boehm in today's Calendar, Orange 
County edition ("Nigerian Musician Sees Music as a Tool," July 27). He uses 
Voltaire as a cover for his own views condoning the right to allow the youth of 
our nation to be exposed to the worst kind of smut proliferated by the likes of 
Luther Campbell's 2 Live Crew. 
</P>
<P>
A quote from the fourth paragraph, "He (Voltaire) would nevertheless defend the 
rappers' right not to be prosecuted for what they have to say, however meager 
its value." Degradation of women and perversion of sex have negative value -- 
much less "meager value"! 
</P>
<P>
I happened to be watching C-Span on July 25 when Rep. Robert K. Dornan 
(R-Garden Grove) addressed the House on the exceedingly detrimental effect some 
2 Live Crew rap lyrics have had on the morals of our youth. He could not repeat 
any of the lyrics because of House decorum. However, he read an article on that 
subject by George Will, using substitute medical words. Having heard what had 
been published by 2 Live Crew, I was dumbfounded that so many condone it in the 
name of the First Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
In the interest of decency, such gory smut must be kept from young 
impressionable minds. It seems a way of life for today's youth to the seek the 
"forbidden apple." I applaud the actions being taken in Florida. I appeal to 
our national leaders to follow suit and do what is needed to bolster decency 
and moral values. 
</P>
<P>
The leaders of our country and the molders of public opinion have an obligation 
to use their power wisely. "One nation, under God, with freedom and justice for 
all." 
</P>
<P>
HARRY E. TERRELL JR. 
</P>
<P>
Santa Ana Heights 
</P>
</TEXT>
