<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: ANACAPA ISLAND; 
</P>
<P>
BRICK LIGHT STATION IS INCLUDED ON NATIONAL REGISTER OF HISTORIC PLACES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAJA RADEVICH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Anacapa Island Light Station was included Friday in the National Register 
of Historic Places. 
</P>
<P>
The brick lighthouse stands 276 feet above the water at the easternmost point 
of Anacapa Island. 
</P>
<P>
The island, which has a land mass of only about one square mile, is 14 miles 
south of Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
Because of a number of maritime disasters, an unattended beacon was installed 
on the island in 1912, followed by construction of the lighthouse. 
</P>
<P>
Members of the U.S. Coast Guard lived on Anacapa and staffed the lighthouse 
until it was made fully automatic in 1969. 
</P>
<P>
The former Coast Guard buildings now house a National Park complex. 
</P>
<P>
Members of the Coast Guard Station on Channel Islands travel to the lighthouse 
once a month to check on the still-functioning light, foghorn, radio beacon and 
generator. MAJA RADEVICH 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Anacapa Island lighthouse is now listed on National Register of Historic 
Places. MARK BOSTER / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
