</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Court Backs Agency's Right to Sue Brokers: A federal appeals court ruled that 
the Securities Investor Protection Corp., an agency created by Congress to 
protect securities investors, can sue fraudulent brokers for racketeering and 
seek triple damages. The 9th U.S. Circuit Court said SIPC can use the powerful 
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act in civil suits against 
brokers. SIPC reimburses customers of failed brokers and can appoint a receiver 
to sell or liquidate an insolvent brokerage that has violated the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
