<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFFICER SUSPENDED FOR FAILING TO HELP WOMAN WHO FROZE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PHILADELPHIA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A police officer has been suspended without pay for failing to help a homeless 
woman who was dying from exposure to the cold in December, police said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
Officer Raymond Ruczynski, 43, a 19-year veteran of the police force, was 
suspended this week for 10 days on the recommendation of the Police Board of 
Inquiry, police Capt. Richard DeLise said. 
</P>
<P>
Nearly an hour after the officer reported to police headquarters on Dec. 16 
that the woman was drunk and had refused assistance, Mary Dennis, 59, was found 
frozen to death on a bench at a city bus stop. 
</P>
<P>
Police Commissioner Willie Williams said Ruczynski should have taken the woman 
to a hospital and consulted his supervisors. The Fraternal Order of Police was 
expected to appeal the suspension. 
</P>
</TEXT>
