<HEADLINE>
<P>
BACKGROUND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
First spotted in Van Nuys in 1988, the ash whitefly has spread north to 
Sacramento and south to the U.S.-Mexico border. 
</P>
<P>
The pinhead-sized insect sucks the juice from the leaves of shade and 
ornamental trees, often defoliating them, and excretes a sticky sap that coats 
cars, patios and sidewalks. Pesticides are ineffective because of the 
whitefly's huge numbers, and the insect has no natural predators in California. 
So scientists have released two imported enemies -- a stingless wasp and a 
ladybird beetle -- to prey on the irksome pest. 
</P>
